[[Image:Bluff_Beach.jpg|thumb|right|200px| Bluff Beach Davit]]
'''Brown Point''' (also known as Point Brown) is a [[headland]] located in the [[Australia|Australian state]] of [[South Australia]] on the west coast of [[Yorke Peninsula]] overlooking [[Hardwicke Bay]] about {{convert|12|km}} west of [[Minlaton, South Australia|Minlaton]].  Since 1999, it has been located within the gazetted locality of [[Bluff Beach, South Australia|Bluff Beach]].<ref name="LMV">{{cite web |title=Search results for ‘Brown Point, PT' with the following datasets being selected - 'Suburbs and Localities', 'Government Towns', 'Counties', 'Local Government Areas', 'SA Government Regions’ and 'Gazetteer' |url= http://location.sa.gov.au/viewer/?map=roads&x=137.52923&y=-34.73866&z=13&uids=19,105&pinx=137.479150&piny=-34.732680&pinTitle=Location&pinText=Brown+Point,+Pt |website=Location SA Map Viewer|publisher=Government of South Australia|accessdate=11 May 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Citation | author1=South Australia. Department of Marine and Harbors (DMH)| title=The Waters of South Australia a series of charts, sailing notes and coastal photographs | publication-date=1985 | publisher=Dept. of Marine and Harbors, South Australia | pages=Chart 24 |isbn=978-0-7243-7603-2}}</ref>

==Davits==
{{Unreferenced section|date=May 2016}}
Brown Point with its boat winching system is unique, and is a proven [[tourist attraction]].  [[Photograph]]s of these "Davits" are exhibited nationally in tourist and travel agencies and also on souvenirs and post cards. The manual winching method for raising and lowering boats from cliff to water with the aid of stable uprights, cables and supports, was introduced by George Parsons and Fred Schwarz in the 1920s and it has proved to be a very assured and convenient way of safe guarding a craft in bad weather over the years. Today the [[fiberglass|fibreglass]] boat has replaced the clinker or wooden boat on account of easy maintenance etc. and trailers have replaced the winching system.

